article.description: Becky Hammon scored 15 of her 19 points in the second half, and the Liberty rallied to beat the last-place Sting 73-65 on Sunday.
article.headline: Hammon sparks Liberty rally with 15 second-half points
article.linkText: Liberty sting Sting with second-half rallly
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- Becky Hammon led another second-half comeback
for the New York Liberty.

Hammon scored 15 of her 19 points after the break, and the
Liberty rallied to beat the last-place Charlotte Sting 73-65 on
Sunday.

"I needed to be more aggressive," Hammon said. "You just want
to stay in your stuff and get everybody involved. I try to be more
aware and conscious of where my shots are and get ready to shoot."

Hammon was 3-for-4 on 3-pointers in the second half, after
missing all three attempts in the opening 20 minutes.

"You just stay in your rhythm, keep shooting the ball like you
know you're capable of and you know they'll eventually fall," she
said.

Vickie Johnson had 10 points, including three key layups down
the stretch, to help the Liberty (16-13) win their third straight
game -- after trailing at halftime in each. New York remained one
game behind second-place Indiana in the Eastern Conference, and
moved 1½ games ahead of Washington and Detroit.

The Liberty were playing for the first time since losing
All-Star center Ann Wauters for at least four weeks due to a broken
right hand.

"You can't replace someone like Ann Wauters," New York coach
Pat Coyle said. "She's an All-Star, one of the best centers in
this league. You're not going to replace her with one player.
You're going to do it by committee, and that's what we're gong to
do."

Reserves La'Keshia Frett and Cathrine Kraayeveld took advantage
of their extended playing time in Wauters' absence, combining for
15 points and six rebounds in 40 minutes. Erin Thorn added eight
points in 24 minutes off the bench.

"We each have to step up," Kraayeveld said. "You can't really
fill Ann's shoes. She's a big part of this team and she does a
great job of making her presence known. No one has to do anything
spectacular, we all have to come together as a team and do what we
do individually."

Tammy Sutton-Brown led Charlotte (4-25) with 19 points. Tangela
Smith added 14 points and Sheri Sam 13.

The Liberty, who trailed by as many as 10 points early in the
second half, outscored the Sting 22-11 in the final seven minutes.

"They came out aggressively and our intensity wasn't the same
from the first to the second half," Sutton-Brown said.

New York shot 44 percent from the field, including 8-for-20 on
3s, and made 11 of 12 free throws. Charlotte shot 42 percent from
the field, and hit 15 of 17 from the line.

After Adrienne Goodson made a pair of free throws to stretch
Charlotte's lead to 54-51 with 7:58 remaining, Hammon and Thorn hit
consecutive 3s and Johnson made a driving layup to give New York a
five-point lead two minutes later.

Thorn and Johnson made back-to-back layups to give the Liberty a
63-56 lead with 3:26 left, and the Sting got no closer than five
points the rest of the way.

"We just weren't able to capitalize on some of the mismatches
we had created," Charlotte coach Muggsy Bogues said. "They had a
lot of 3-point shots that opened it up for them."

The Sting used an 8-3 run to push their lead to 43-33 about four
minutes into the second half. New York had a 10-0 run, capped by
Hammon's second 3 of the spurt, to take a 46-44 lead with 12:24
remaining in the game.

Sam made consecutive layups to give Charlotte a 52-49 advantage
with just under nine minutes left.

The Liberty missed nine of their first 10 shots, and were 34
percent (11-for-32) in the first half.

The Sting scored seven straight points, capped by Goodson's
fast-break layup, to take a 16-7 lead just over seven minutes into
the game. Charlotte stretched its advantage to as much as 11 in the
period.

Ayana Walker's buzzer-beater at the end of the first half gave
the Sting a 35-27 lead at the break.

Wauters injured her hand early in the second half of the
Liberty's 82-74 double-overtime win at Charlotte on Friday night.
She missed the last 17 regular-season games and the playoffs a year
ago after breaking a bone in her right foot in early July.

The 6-foot-4 center was averaging 13.7 points and 6.6 rebounds
in 28 games this season. She was second in the league with a .541
shooting percentage.
